            <h3>Datatypes</h3>
            <p>Data types are fundamental classifications that specify which type of data a variable can hold in a
                programming language.</p>
            <p>Primitive Data Types: Java has 8 primitive datatypes namely-</p>
            <p><b>Byte:</b> Represents small integers (-128 to 127), useful for conserving memory in large arrays.</p>
            <p><b>Short:</b> Stores small integers (-32,768 to 32,767), often used when memory conservation is critical.</p>
            <p><b>Int:</b> Holds whole numbers (-2^31 to 2^31-1), the most commonly used integer type.</p>
            <p><b>Long:</b> Used to store very large whole numbers, with a wider range than int. It can hold values from -2^63 to 2^63-1. Typically used when you need to work with extremely large integers, such as timestamps, large counts, or when int's range is insufficient.</p>
            <p><b>Float:</b>  Stores decimal numbers with limited precision, suitable for non-critical applications.</p>
            <p><b>Double:</b>  Represents decimal numbers with higher precision, commonly used for most floating-point calculations.</p>
            <p><b>Char:</b> Stores a single character (e.g., 'A' or '3'), used for working with characters and text.</p>
            <p><b>Boolean:</b>Represents true or false values, essential for controlling program flow and logic.</p>
